This is an SAS problem. We have two sides and the included angle.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.7]
 % Lake (shaded)
 ll[AtlasTeal!20] (0,0) ellipse (3 and 1.5);
 at (0,0) { Lake};

 % Points
 (A) at (-2.5,1);
 (B) at (2.8,0.8);
 (C) at (0.5,3);

 % Triangle
 (A) – (C) – (B);
 (A) – (B);

 % Labels
 lldraw (A) circle (2pt) node[left] {$A$};
 lldraw (B) circle (2pt) node[right] {$B$};
 lldraw (C) circle (2pt) node[above] {$C$};

 % Side labels
 at ($(A)!0.5!(C)$) {350 m};
 at ($(B)!0.5!(C)$) {450 m};
 at ($(A)!0.5!(B)$) {?};

 % Angle
 ($(C)!0.4!(A)$) arc (215:323:0.6);
 at (0.5,2.3) { $72°$};
tikzpicture
center

Using the Law of Cosines with $a = CB = 450$, $b = CA = 350$, and $C = 72°$:
$$
 AB^2 &= CA^2 + CB^2 - 2(CA)(CB)\cos C \\
 &= 350^2 + 450^2 - 2(350)(450)\cos 72° \\
 &= 122500 + 202500 - 315000(0.309) \\
 &= 325000 - 97335 \\
 &= 227665
$$
\[
 AB = \sqrt{227665} \approx 477.1 \text{ meters}
\]

The distance across the lake is approximately **477 meters**.
